[[File:Afghanistan Loya Paktia.png|thumb|230px|The [[Afghanistan|Afghan]] provinces of [[Paktia]], [[Paktika]] and [[Khost province|Khost]], and some neighboring areas constitute the Loya Paktia region]] '''Lōya Paktiā''' ({{lang-ps|لويه پکتيا}}; lit. '''Greater Paktia''') is a historical and cultural region of [[Afghanistan]], comprising the modern [[Provinces of Afghanistan|Afghan provinces]] of [[Khost province|Khost]], [[Paktia]], and [[Paktika]], as well as parts of [[Logar Province|Logar]] and [[Ghazni province|Ghazni]],<ref name="ref38valer">[https://books.google.com/books?id=zYgUZtth2qgC 7 Deadly Scenarios: A Military Futurist Explores the Changing Face of War in the 21st Century], Andrew Krepinevich, Random House Digital, Inc., 2010, {{ISBN|9780553384727}}, ''... Paktia was once a unified province with Khost and Paktika in southeast Afghanistan. The three provinces are now referred to as 'Loya Paktia', which means 'The Greater Paktia' ...''</ref> and parts of [[Kurram District|Kurram]] and [[Waziristan]] in [[Pakistan]]. Loya Paktia is vaguely defined by a common culture and history that is connected to the local indigenous tribes that reside in the region. Particular styles of clothing, articles of clothing, turban styles, turban cloth colors, dialects of [[Pashto language]], etc. may sometimes be associated with specific tribes indigenous to Loya Paktia and thus integrate themselves into regional culture. For instance, a Pashtun tribesman from [[Loy Kandahar]] may quickly recognize a Pashtun from Loya Paktia based upon his turban (or lungee) style and color. Likewise, a Pashtun from Loya Paktia may recognize someone from Loy Kandahar based upon his unique style of collarless [[Shalwar Kameez|kameez]] (shirt) with specific embroidered patterns on the front. There are many subtle and intricate cultural indicators of this type that are not recorded in any known [[recorded history|written history]] but simply known and observed by the tribesmen of the various Pashtun regions of [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]].
==Main settlements== The largest city of the region is [[Khost]], while other cities of Loya Paktia include [[Zurmat]] (largest city of Paktia Province), [[Gardez]] (capital of Paktia Province), [[Urgun]] (largest city of Paktika), and [[Sharana]] (capital of Paktika).
Other main towns of Loya Paktia are [[Sardeh Band]] (Ghazni), [[Charkh, Afghanistan|Charkh]] (Logar), [[Tari Mangal]] (Kurram), [[Angur Ada]] (partly in [[South Waziristan]]), [[Yakubi]], [[Tani, Khost|Tani]], [[Dadwal]], [[Aryob]], [[Khandkhel]], [[Tsamkani]], [[Zarghun Shar, Paktika|Zarghun Shar]], [[Wazakhwa]], and [[Zerok]].
==Demography== The population mostly consists of [[Pashtuns]] from various tribes under the larger [[Karlani]] and [[Ghilji]] confederacies. Predominant tribes with notable large populations native to Loya Paktia include [[Zadran (Pashtun tribe)|Zadran]], [[Zazi]], [[Mangal (Pashtun tribe)|Mangal]], Tani, Sabari, [[Sulaimankhel]], [[Kharoti]], [[Wazir (Pashtun tribe)|Wazir]], and Gurbaz. [[Kochi people|Kochian]] are common in the region throughout the year who still live a nomadic lifestyle.
