{{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Keen | other_name = {{lang-gd|Monadh Caoin}} | photo = The view into Glen Esk, From West Knock - geograph.org.uk - 566327.jpg | elevation_m = 939 | elevation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/munros/mount-keen |title= walkhighlands Mount Keen|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |publisher=walkhighlands.co.uk |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> | pronunciation = {{IPA-gd|ˈmɔnəɣ ˈkʰɯːɲ|lang}} | prominence = {{c.}} 314 m | listing = [[Munro]], [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]] | location = [[Aberdeenshire]] / [[Angus, Scotland]] | range = [[Grampian Mountains]] | grid_ref_UK = NO409869 }} '''Mount Keen''' ({{lang-gd|Monadh Caoin}}) is a 939&nbsp;m (3,081 feet) high [[mountain]] in [[Scotland]] and the most easterly [[Munro]]. It can be accessed from several directions, South from [[Glen Mark]], North from [[Glen Tanar]], and East to [[Braid Cairn]]. It is a moderate walk which is most popularly started by [[mountain bike]], riding through the native [[Caledonian Forest|Caledonian pine forest]] of [[Glen Tanar]] from [[Aboyne]]. On a good day, the [[Cairngorms]], especially [[Lochnagar]], can be seen. The summit is marked by a [[Triangulation station|trig point]].
==Path quality == Path quality is very good on the approach to the mountain. There is a wide forestry track most of the way to the foot of the mountain if approaching from [[Aboyne]] and [[Glen Tanar]]. Path quality on the mountain itself is moderate. An effort has been made to widen and ensure the path remains water free, however rain has left some shallow channels in the path. Further up, the path becomes rocky yet easy to walk on unless in icy conditions.
== Summit == Mobile phone reception is excellent from the summit for Vodafone and O2 users and possibly many others as there is a direct line of sight with the Durris mast. There is a steep drop to the East of the summit so in icy conditions care should be taken. Limited shelter can be taken beside large boulders and a trig point allows walkers to collect their bearings.
In 2002 the footbridge at the base of Mount Keen on the [[Glen Tanar]] side was washed away. To allow for improved access to this popular [[Munro]] the bridge has been replaced.
